{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524172","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524172"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:02:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13977"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13977"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.08,0.03,0.53,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6611"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55880"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6611"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13977"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41428"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"459"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13374"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37411"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55880"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of severe, sudden onset upper abdominal pain. She has experienced several weeks of intermittent epigastric pain with no changes to her bowel habits or other associated symptoms. She has a medical history of rheumatoid arthritis, gastro-oesophageal reflux disease and dyslipidaemia. Her regular medications include sulfasalazine, atorvastatin, pantoprazole and as required meloxicam. She does not smoke, but drinks four to six glasses of wine daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and in pain. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. She has tenderness and guarding in the epigastrium. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Infected pancreatic pseudocyst","Gallbladder perforation","Diverticular abscess","Perforated gastric ulcer","Liver abscess"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis to explain this presentation is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eperforated gastric ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E. The CT abdomen demonstrates a localised collection anterior to the stomach consistent with a contained perforation. The patient\u0027s presenting symptoms, examination findings and NSAID use are also supportive of this diagnosis. NSAIDs are a well-known risk factor for gastric ulcers and their complications, including perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic pseudocysts \u003C/strong\u003Etypically develop as a complication of acute or chronic pancreatitis and can become infected. Although this can present with upper abdominal pain and fever, sudden onset pain is not typical. While the patient has a history of excess alcohol consumption, she has no history of pancreatitis making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGallbladder perforation\u003C/strong\u003E usually develops as a complication of acute cholecystitis, presenting with right upper quadrant pain, fever, and vomiting. While the gallbladder is not visualised in this CT image, the clinical presentation favours peptic ulcer disease over cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticular abscess\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with lower abdominal pain, often in the left lower quadrant. There would also likely be a history of diverticulitis symptoms, which may include abdominal pain, abnormal bowel habits and rectal bleeding, which are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver abscess\u003C/strong\u003E can cause upper abdominal pain and fever, but usually has a more gradual onset. The lesion on CT lies anterior to the liver, rather than within it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe collection in this case would be amenable to percutaneous drainage. Once acute management of the perforation is completed, the patient should have a follow-up endoscopy arranged to confirm ulcer healing and exclude gastric malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Perforated gastric ulcers can present with severe upper abdominal pain and may be associated with recent NSAID use.","CT scan is useful in diagnosing complications of gastric ulcers, such as perforation and localized collections.","Follow-up endoscopy is important to confirm healing of gastric ulcers and rule out malignancy."],"references":["Almadi M, Lu Y, Alali A, et al. Peptic ulcer disease. Lancet. 2024;404:68-81. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/article/S0140-6736(24)00155-7/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41428"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13977"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20870"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20870"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/O2egMPo9BdvRMsTGQXqDVbwwhkbPxJ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/O2egMPo9BdvRMsTGQXqDVb